<p><a name="Cincinnati"></a><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="4"><b>Cincinnati janitors</b></font><br>
<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="2"><b>By Shane Johnson</b></font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">CINCINNATI--More than 125 people representing three labor unions and several churches picketed the building of the <i>Cincinnati Enquirer, </i>the mouthpiece of the city's right-wingers, on November 23. The picket was called by janitors as part of the Justice for Janitors campaign and was organized by Service Employees International Union Local 3. <p>
Immigrant janitors have been threatened by their employer, Jancoa Janitorial Services, with deportation and wage cuts if they continue their organizing. Most of the janitors are from Guatemala and make a paltry $7.50 an hour while working 35 hours a week. The building's owner, Duke Realty, which also employs Jancoa janitors, is currently facing five unfair labor practice charges by the National Labor Relations Board. <p>
"Our families and our communities can't live like this," one janitor said of the poverty wages and lack of health care. <p>
Duke Realty responded to the picket by sending employees outside to videotape picketers--and refused to meet with a delegation sent in to negotiate.<p>
This picket needs to be a stepping stone to future actions.<p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="#Top">Back to the top</a></font><br>
